{"title_page": "John Howard Davies", "text_new": "{{short description|English actor, and television producer and director}}\n{{other people||John Davies (disambiguation){{!}}John Davies}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = John Howard Davies\n| image        = John_Howard_Davies.jpg\n| imagesize    =\n| caption      =\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1939|3|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Paddington]], [[London]], England\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|2011|8|22|1939|3|9|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Blewbury]], [[Oxfordshire]], England\n| other_names  =\n| occupation   = Actor, director, producer\n| years_active = \n| spouse       = Leonie <small>(unknown)</small><br>{{marriage|Linda|2005|2011|end=his death}}\n| children     = 2\n}}\n'''John Howard Davies''' (9 March 1939{{spaced ndash}}22 August 2011)<ref name=\"Telegraph\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/tv-radio-obituaries/8718897/John-Howard-Davies.html Obituary: John Howard Davies,] ''Daily Telegraph'', 23 August 2011</ref> was an English [[child actor]] who later became a [[television director]] and [[television producer|producer]].\n\n==Biography==\nDavies was born in [[Paddington]], London, the son of [[Jack Davies (screenwriter)|Jack Davies]], a [[film critic]] and prolific [[screenwriter|scriptwriter]] for mainly Gainsborough and Elstree studios, and the novelist Dorothy Davies.<ref name = guardobit/>\n\n==Child actor==\nKnown to his friends as JHD, his credits as a [[child actor]] include the title role at  the age of nine in [[David Lean]]'s production ''[[Oliver Twist (1948 film)|Oliver Twist]]'' (1948), followed by ''[[The Rocking Horse Winner (film)|The Rocking Horse Winner]]'' (1949), ''[[Tom Brown's Schooldays (1951 film)|Tom Brown's Schooldays]]'' (1951) and a few episodes of the TV series ''[[The Adventures of William Tell|William Tell]]'' (1958).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18463641 |title=\"JUNIOR ANGEL\" AS FILM OLIVER TWIST. |newspaper=[[The Sunday Herald (Sydney)|The Sunday Herald]] |location=Sydney |date=30 January 1949 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |page=5 Supplement: Magazine Section |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nAfter a basic education at [[Haileybury and Imperial Service College|Haileybury School]],<ref name = guardobit/> he gained further education in [[Grenoble]], France, followed by [[national service]] in the [[Royal Navy|Navy]].<ref name=\"Telegraph2\">{{cite news\n|title=John Howard Davies\n|date=24 August 2011\n|work=The Daily Telegraph\n|pages=29 (Obituaries)\n}}</ref>\n\n==Adult career==\nAfter being discharged from the Navy, Davies worked in the [[City of London]] financial sector, and then as a carpet salesman. He relocated to [[Melbourne, Australia]], where he returned to acting and met his first wife, Leonie, when they both appeared in ''[[The Sound of Music]]''. He was stage manager for ''The Sound of Music'' for two years touring Australia and New Zealand.<ref name=\"Gaughan\">{{cite news|first=Gavin|last=Gaughan|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/john-howard-davies-child-star-of-david-leans-oliver-twist-who-became-head-of-comedy-at-the-bbc-2343216.html|title=Obituary: John Howard Davies|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|publisher=Independent Print Ltd.|location=London, England|date=25 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe is best known for his adult career as a director and producer of several highly successful [[British sitcom]]s. Returning to the UK, Davies became a [[BBC]] production assistant during 1966, and was promoted to producer in 1968.<ref name=\"Oliver\">{{cite web|first=John|last=Oliver|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/people/id/501222/index.html|title=Davies, John Howard (1939\u2013)|website=BFI.org|accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref> During this early period Davies worked on sketch shows such as ''[[The World of Beachcomber]]'' (1968), the earliest episodes of ''[[Monty Python's Flying Circus]]'' (1969) and ''[[The Goodies (TV series)|The Goodies]]'' (1970\u201372). He also directed the young [[Anthony Hopkins]] in the first episode of the Biography series in \"Danton\", written by [[Arden Winch]].  He also worked on ''[[All Gas and Gaiters]]'' (1969\u201370) and the seventh series of ''[[Steptoe and Son]]'' in 1972.\n\nHe briefly left the BBC to become managing director of EMI Television Productions in 1973,<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> but soon returned to the corporation.<ref name=\"Oliver\"/> From this time came ''[[Fawlty Towers]]'' (1975). Casting [[Prunella Scales]] as [[Sybil Fawlty]] was Davies' idea, as the actress the producers wanted to cast turned down the part.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> Davies was producer for all four series of ''[[The Good Life (1975 TV series)|The Good Life]]'' (1975\u201378).<ref>{{cite ODNB|first=Christopher|last=Webber|title=Davies, John Howard (1939\u20132011)|date= Jan 2015|id= 104018|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/public/dnb/104018.html}}</ref>\n\nHe was the [[BBC]]'s Head of Comedy from 1977\u201382, then Head of Light Entertainment, before joining [[Thames Television]] in 1985. Thames was then an [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] contractor, for which Davies was head of [[light entertainment]] from 1988.<ref name=\"Gaughan\"/> During the last role he was cited by the [[news media|popular press]] as the man who fired comedian [[Benny Hill]] when the company decided not to renew his contract<ref name = guardobit>{{cite news|first=Matthew|last=Sweet|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/aug/24/john-howard-davies-obituary|title=Obituary: John Howard Davies|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=24 August 2011}}</ref> after a connection lasting 20 years. He told Hill's biographer [[Mark Lewisohn]], \"It's very dangerous to have a show on ITV that doesn't appeal to women, because they hold the purse strings, in a sense.\"<ref name=\"Gaughan\"/> He was later appointed a controller of BBC.\n\nDuring this period he worked on ''[[No Job for a Lady]]'' (1990\u201392) and ''[[Mr. Bean]]'' (1990), returning to the BBC later in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-14634360|title=Fawlty Towers producer John Howard Davies dies at 72|website=[[BBC News]]|date=23 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nDavies died from [[cancer]]<ref>[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=139880148 \"TV Comedy Producer John Howard Davies Dies At 72\"], NPR citing the Associated Press, 23 August 2011</ref> on 22 August 2011 at his home in [[Blewbury]], [[Oxfordshire]]. He married his third wife, Linda,<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> in 2005.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! {{Tooltip|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 1948 || ''[[Oliver Twist (1948 film)|Oliver Twist]]'' || [[Oliver Twist (character)|Oliver Twist]] || <ref name = guardobit/>\n|-\n| 1949 || ''[[The Rocking Horse Winner (film)|The Rocking Horse Winner]]'' || Paul Grahame || <ref name = guardobit/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1951\n| ''[[Tom Brown's Schooldays (1951 film)|Tom Brown's Schooldays]]'' || [[Tom Brown (character)|Tom Brown]] || <ref name = guardobit/>\n|-\n| ''[[The Magic Box]]'' || Maurice Freise-Greene || <ref name = guardobit/>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*John Holmstrom, ''The Moving Picture Boy: An International Encyclopaedia from 1895 to 1995'', Norwich, Michael Russell, 1996, p.&nbsp;211.\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|203791}}\n*[http://tviv.org/John_Howard_Davies The TV IV \u2013 John Howard Davies]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, John Howard}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:BBC television producers]]\n[[Category:English male child actors]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English television directors]]\n[[Category:English television producers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Haileybury and Imperial Service College]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in England]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer]]\n[[Category:People from Blewbury]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English actor, and television producer and director}}\n{{other people||John Davies (disambiguation){{!}}John Davies}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = John Howard Davies\n| image        = John_Howard_Davies.jpg\n| imagesize    =\n| caption      =\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1939|3|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Paddington]], [[London]], England\n| death_date   = {{Death date and age|2011|8|22|1939|3|9|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Blewbury]], [[Oxfordshire]], England\n| other_names  =\n| occupation   = Actor, director, producer\n| years_active = \n| spouse       = Leonie <small>(unknown)</small><br>{{marriage|Linda|2005|2011|end=his death}}\n| children     = 2\n}}\n'''John Howard Davies''' (9 March 1939{{spaced ndash}}22 August 2011)<ref name=\"Telegraph\">[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/culture-obituaries/tv-radio-obituaries/8718897/John-Howard-Davies.html Obituary: John Howard Davies,] ''Daily Telegraph'', 23 August 2011</ref> was an English [[child actor]] who later became a [[television director]] and [[television producer|producer]].\n\n==Biography==\nDavies was born in [[Paddington]], London, the son of [[Jack Davies (screenwriter)|Jack Davies]], a [[film critic]] and prolific [[screenwriter|scriptwriter]] for mainly Gainsborough and Elstree studios, and the novelist Dorothy Davies.<ref name = guardobit/>\n\n==Child actor==\nKnown to his friends as JHD, his credits as a [[child actor]] include the title role at  the age of nine in [[David Lean]]'s production ''[[Oliver Twist (1948 film)|Oliver Twist]]'' (1948), followed by ''[[The Rocking Horse Winner (film)|The Rocking Horse Winner]]'' (1949), ''[[Tom Brown's Schooldays (1951 film)|Tom Brown's Schooldays]]'' (1951) and a few episodes of the TV series ''[[The Adventures of William Tell|William Tell]]'' (1958).<ref>{{cite news |url=http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article18463641 |title=\"JUNIOR ANGEL\" AS FILM OLIVER TWIST. |newspaper=[[The Sunday Herald (Sydney)|The Sunday Herald]] |location=Sydney |date=30 January 1949 |accessdate=7 July 2012 |page=5 Supplement: Magazine Section |via=National Library of Australia}}</ref>\n\nAfter a basic education at [[Haileybury and Imperial Service College|Haileybury School]],<ref name = guardobit/> he gained further education in [[Grenoble]], France, followed by [[national service]] in the [[Royal Navy|Navy]].<ref name=\"Telegraph2\">{{cite news\n|title=John Howard Davies\n|date=24 August 2011\n|work=The Daily Telegraph\n|pages=29 (Obituaries)\n}}</ref>\n\n==Adult career==\nAfter being discharged from the Navy, Davies worked in the [[City of London]] financial sector, and then as a carpet salesman. He relocated to [[Melbourne, Australia]], where he returned to acting and met his first wife, Leonie, when they both appeared in ''[[The Sound of Music]]''. He was stage manager for ''The Sound of Music'' for two years touring Australia and New Zealand.<ref name=\"Gaughan\">{{cite news|first=Gavin|last=Gaughan|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/john-howard-davies-child-star-of-david-leans-oliver-twist-who-became-head-of-comedy-at-the-bbc-2343216.html|title=Obituary: John Howard Davies|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|publisher=Independent Print Ltd.|location=London, England|date=25 August 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe is best known for his adult career as a director and producer of several highly successful [[British sitcom]]s. Returning to the UK, Davies became a [[BBC]] production assistant during 1966, and was promoted to producer in 1968.<ref name=\"Oliver\">{{cite web|first=John|last=Oliver|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/people/id/501222/index.html|title=Davies, John Howard (1939\u2013)|website=BFI.org|accessdate=November 27, 2019}}</ref> During this early period Davies worked on sketch shows such as ''[[The World of Beachcomber]]'' (1968), the earliest episodes of ''[[Monty Python's Flying Circus]]'' (1969) and ''[[The Goodies (TV series)|The Goodies]]'' (1970\u201372). He also directed the young [[Anthony Hopkins]] in the first episode of the Biography series in \"Danton\", written by [[Arden Winch]].  He also worked on ''[[All Gas and Gaiters]]'' (1969\u201370) and the seventh series of ''[[Steptoe and Son]]'' in 1972.\n\nHe briefly left the BBC to become managing director of EMI Television Productions in 1973,<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> but soon returned to the corporation.<ref name=\"Oliver\"/> From this time came ''[[Fawlty Towers]]'' (1975). Casting [[Prunella Scales]] as [[Sybil Fawlty]] was Davies' idea, as the actress the producers wanted to cast turned down the part.<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> Davies was producer for all four series of ''[[The Good Life (1975 TV series)|The Good Life]]'' (1975\u201378).<ref>{{cite ODNB|first=Christopher|last=Webber|title=Davies, John Howard (1939\u20132011)|date= Jan 2015|id= 104018|url=http://www.oxforddnb.com/public/dnb/104018.html}}</ref>\n\nHe was the [[BBC]]'s Head of Comedy from 1977\u201382, then Head of Light Entertainment, before joining [[Thames Television]] in 1985. Thames was then an [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] contractor, for which Davies was head of [[light entertainment]] from 1988.<ref name=\"Gaughan\"/> During the last role he was cited by the [[news media|popular press]] as the man who fired comedian [[Benny Hill]] when the company decided not to renew his contract<ref name = guardobit>{{cite news|first=Matthew|last=Sweet|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2011/aug/24/john-howard-davies-obituary|title=Obituary: John Howard Davies|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|date=24 August 2011}}</ref> after a connection lasting 20 years. He told Hill's biographer [[Mark Lewisohn]], \"It's very dangerous to have a show on ITV that doesn't appeal to women, because they hold the purse strings, in a sense.\"<ref name=\"Gaughan\"/> He was later appointed a controller of BBC.\n\nDuring this period he worked on ''[[No Job for a Lady]]'' (1990\u201392) and ''[[Mr. Bean]]'' (1990), returning to the BBC later in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-14634360|title=Fawlty Towers producer John Howard Davies dies at 72|website=[[BBC News]]|date=23 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nDavies died from [[cancer]]<ref>[https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=139880148 \"TV Comedy Producer John Howard Davies Dies At 72\"], NPR citing the Associated Press, 23 August 2011</ref> on 22 August 2011 at his home in [[Blewbury]], [[Oxfordshire]]. He married his third wife, Linda,<ref name=\"Telegraph\"/> in 2005.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! {{Tooltip|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n| 1948 || ''[[Oliver Twist (1948 film)|Oliver Twist]]'' || [[Oliver Twist (character)|Oliver Twist]] || <ref name = guardobit/>\n|-\n| 1949 || ''[[The Rocking Horse Winner (film)|The Rocking Horse Winner]]'' || Paul Grahame || <ref name = guardobit/>\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1951\n| ''[[Tom Brown's Schooldays (1951 film)|Tom Brown's Schooldays]]'' || [[Tom Brown (character)|Tom Brown]] || <ref name = guardobit/>\n|-\n| ''[[The Magic Box]]'' || Maurice Freise-Greene || <ref name = guardobit/>\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*John Holmstrom, ''The Moving Picture Boy: An International Encyclopaedia from 1895 to 1995'', Norwich, Michael Russell, 1996, p.&nbsp;211.\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|203791}}\n*[http://tviv.org/John_Howard_Davies The TV IV \u2013 John Howard Davies]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Davies, John Howard}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:BBC television producers]]\n[[Category:English male child actors]]\n[[Category:English male film actors]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:English television directors]]\n[[Category:English television producers]]\n[[Category:People educated at Haileybury and Imperial Service College]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer in England]]\n[[Category:Deaths from cancer]]\n", "name_user": "Verica Atrebatum", "label": "safe", "comment": "cat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Howard_Davies"}
{"title_page": "Adam Stefan Sapieha", "text_new": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type = Cardinal\n| honorific-prefix = His Eminence \n| name = Adam Stefan Sapieha\n| honorific-suffix = \n| title = [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|Cardinal]], [[Archbishop of Krak\u00f3w]]\n| image = Adam Stefan Sapieha (1867-1951).jpg\n| imagesize = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| church = \n| archdiocese = \n| province = \n| metropolis = \n| diocese = \n| see = \n| elected = \n| appointed = 18 February 1946\n| term_start = 18 February 1946\n| quashed = \n| term_end = 21 July 1951\n| predecessor = [[Jan Puzyna de Kosielsko]]\n| opposed = \n| successor = [[Eugeniusz Baziak]] (apostolic administrator)\n| other_post = Cardinal-Priest of S. Maria Nuova\n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination = 1 October 1893\n| ordained_by = [[Jan Maurycy Pawel Puzyna de Kosielsko]]\n| consecration = 17 December 1911\n| consecrated_by = [[Pope Pius X]]\n| cardinal = 18 February 1946\n| rank =\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name = Prince Adam Stefan Stanis\u0142aw Bonfatiusz J\u00f3zef Sapieha\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=y|1867|5|14}}\n| birth_place = [[Krasiczyn]], [[Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria]], [[Austrian Empire]] (now in Poland)\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=y|1951|7|21|1867|5|14}}\n| death_place = [[Krak\u00f3w]], Poland\n| buried = \n| nationality = Polish\n| religion = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| residence = \n| parents = Adam Stanis\u0142aw Sapieha-Kodenski<br />Jadwiga Klementyna Sanguszko-Lubartowicza\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| alma_mater = \n| motto = \n| coat_of_arms = Card Sapieha COA.png\n<!---------- Sainthood ---------->\n| feast_day = \n| venerated = \n| saint_title = \n| beatified_date = \n| beatified_place = \n| beatified_by = \n| canonized_date = \n| canonized_place = \n| canonized_by = \n| attributes = \n| patronage = \n| shrine = \n| suppressed_date =\n<!---------- Other ---------->\n| other = \n}}\n{{Infobox nobility|type\n| name = Adam Stefan Sapieha \n| CoA = [[Lis coat of arms]] [[File:Herb Sapieh\u00f3w.PNG|150px]]\n| more = no\n| noble family = [[Sapieha]]\n| house-type = Szlachta\n}}\n{{Infobox cardinalstyles\n| cardinal name = Adam Stefan Sapieha\n| image = Card Sapieha COA.png\n| dipstyle = [[His Eminence]]\n| offstyle = Your Eminence\n| relstyle = (autofilled)\n| See = Krak\u00f3w\n}}\n\n'''Prince Adam Stefan Stanis\u0142aw Bonifacy J\u00f3zef Sapieha''' ({{IPA-pl|\u02c8adam \u02c8st\u025bfan sa\u02c8p\u02b2\u025bxa}}; 14 May 1867 \u2013 23 July 1951) was a [[Poland|Polish]] [[cardinal (Catholicism)|cardinal]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]] who served as [[Archbishop of Krak\u00f3w]]. Between 1922\u20131923 he was a senator of the [[Second Polish Republic]] (Polish ''Rzeczpospolita''). In 1946, [[Pope Pius XII]] created him Cardinal.\n\n==Early life==\nSapieha was born in 1867 in the castle of [[Krasiczyn]], then part of the [[Austrian Empire]]. His family, originally from the [[Grand Duchy of Lithuania]], were members of the Polish [[nobility]]. He was the youngest of the seven children of Prince [[Adam Stanis\u0142aw Sapieha|Adam Stanis\u0142aw Sapieha-Kodenski]] and Princess Jadwiga Klementyna [[House of Sanguszko|Sanguszko-Lubartowicza]], daughter of [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Hieronim Sanguszko]]. His elder brother prince [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Leon Sapieha]] is the great-grand father of [[Mathilde of Belgium|Queen Mathilde of the Belgians]].\n\n==Education and early vocation==\nAfter graduating from [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]] in [[Lw\u00f3w]] in 1886, he enrolled in the Law Department at the [[University of Vienna]], starting simultaneously law studies at [[Institut Catholique de Paris|Institut Catholique]] in [[Lille]]. In 1887 on the basis of his certificate from the [[University of Vienna]] Sapieha continued studies at the [[Jagiellonian University]] in [[Krak\u00f3w]]. After two years he passed the examination and returned to [[Vienna]] for further studies, where he remained until 1890, obtaining the certificate of completion. \n\nIn the same year he began theological studies at the [[University of Innsbruck]], and in 1892 signed up for the third year of the [[Roman Catholic Seminary in Lviv|Major Roman Catholic Theological Seminary in Lviv]]. He was then educated at the [[Pontifical Gregorian University]] in Rome, where he was also [[Priesthood (Catholic Church)|ordained as priest]] of [[Lviv]] (Lw\u00f3w, Lemberg) on 1 October 1893 by Bishop [[Jan Puzyna de Kosielsko]] (later [[Bishop of Krak\u00f3w]] and Cardinal). Father Sapieha then did pastoral work in the Archdiocese of Lviv before in October 1895 he started further studies in Rome, where he obtained a doctorate of civil and canon law at the [[Pontifical Ecclesiastical Academy]]. At the same time he studied diplomacy at the [[Pontifical Academy of Ecclesiastical Nobles]].\n\nAfter returning to the home country in 1897, he was designated vice-rector of the diocesan seminary in Lviv and eventually became its [[Rector (academia)|rector]]. He resigned because he was discouraged by the imposed rules of education of young priests. After a half-year trip across the [[United States|United States of America]], he was designated a vicar of the St. Nicholas congregation in Lviv in October 1902. In 1905 Sapieha was appointed a [[papal chamberlain]], and sent to Rome where he was a consultant on matters concerning the Roman Catholic Church in Poland, in the [[History of Poland|annexed territories]], the realization of an idea by Lviv [[Armenian Catholic]] Archbishop [[J\u00f3zef Teodorowicz]] (who was the Sapieha's long-term friend)<ref>Wielki Zapomniany, ks.Tadeusz Isakowicz-Zaleski. [http://lwow.home.pl/ormianie/teodorowicz.html ks. abp J\u00f3zef Teodorowicz (1864\u20131938)].</ref> to have a representative of the Roman Catholic Church in Poland at the [[Roman Curia]].\n\n==Bishop==\nSapieha was appointed [[Bishop of Krak\u00f3w]] on 24 November 1911 and was consecrated by [[Pope Pius X]] in the [[Sistine Chapel]] on 7 December of the same year. In 1915, he established a relief committee for victims of World War I.\n\nAfter World War I, Sapieha became a vocal opponent of the new [[concordat]] negotiated between the [[Holy See]] and the newly resurrected Polish state. He argued that the Polish Church should be completely independent of the state and that its primate should be the [[Archbishop of Warsaw]]. This attitude led to a conflict with [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|Cardinal]] [[Achille Ratti]], [[Pope Benedict XV]]'s nuncio who himself later became [[Pope]], during the first post-war congress of Polish bishops in [[Gniezno]] held 26\u201330 August 1919. Sapieha thought that the Polish should decide their affairs without outside influence and asked Ratti to leave the conference room. Sapieha was not elevated to the cardinalate by Ratti after he became Pope [[Pius XI]] in 1922.\n\nIn 1922, Sapieha was elected senator from the [[Christian Union of National Unity]] party. He ordered a memorial service and issued a proclamation on the assassination of [[Gabriel Narutowicz]]. It was the only speech he delivered as a senator because papal mandate at the time prohibited clergy from holding public office. He resigned on 9 March 1923.\n\nSapieha was appointed Metropolitan Archbishop in 1925 when the Diocese of Krak\u00f3w was elevated to the rank of Archdiocese. He received a [[honorary degree|degree honoris causa]] from the [[Jagiellonian University]] in 1926. In September 1930, after opposition leaders were arrested and placed in confinement at [[Brest Fortress]], Archbishops Sapieha and Teodorowicz strongly criticized the government. Despite this, and other occasional disagreements with the government, Sapieha was awarded the [[Order of the White Eagle (Poland)|Order of the White Eagle]] in 1936.\n\nIn 1937, Sapieha, who had opposed the [[J\u00f3zef Pi\u0142sudski|Pilsudski]] regime (sanacja), made the controversial decision to move Pi\u0142sudski's body, within [[Wawel Cathedral|Wawel's Cathedral]], from [[St. Leonard's Crypt]] to the crypt under the Silver Bells.<ref>Historical Dictionary of Poland, 966-1945. Jerzy Jan Lerski, 1996.[https://books.google.com/books?id=S6aUBuWPqywC&pg=PA525 Google Print, page 525].</ref><ref>Annual Register, edited by Edmund Burke. [https://books.google.com/books?id=ASoNAAAAIAAJ&dq=sapieha+pilsudski+crypt&q=sacred&pgis=1#search Google Print, page 202].</ref>\n\nIn 1939 he asked [[Pope Pius XI]] to accept his resignation due to age and failing health, but the pope refused. After the death of Pius XI, he repeated his request to the new pope, [[Pius XII]] on 19 June 1939. In anticipation of the upcoming war and at [[J\u00f3zef Beck]]'s instigation he withdrew his resignation.\n\n===Activities during the Second World War===\nDuring World War II, while Primate [[August Hlond]] was in France, Sapieha was the de facto head of the Polish church in jurisdictions directly annexed by the [[Third Reich]] (primate Hlond was represented by Walenty Dymek, auxiliary bishop of Pozna\u0144) and was one of the main leaders of the nation{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}}. One of the most important organisations to which he belonged was the [[National Council of Welfare]], created on the model of [[Caritas (charity)|Caritas]]. From the war's start of the Nazi occupation, he was an independence activist, working with the [[Polish government-in-exile]].\n\nIn August 1944, Sapieha was forced to operate the Polish seminary in secret because the Germans began killing seminarians whenever they found them. He moved his students (including the future [[Pope John Paul II]], Karol Wojty\u0142a) into the [[Bishop's Palace, Krak\u00f3w|Bishop's Palace in Krak\u00f3w]] to finish their training during the Nazi [[Occupation of Poland]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7ICFN4iJpgwC&pg=PA280 |title=Social Memory and History: Anthropological perspectives|first1=Jacob J. |last1=Climo|first2=Maria G.|last2=Cattell|year=2002 |publisher=Rowman Altamira|isbn=0759101787|page=280}}</ref>\n\nSapieha's biographer, Jacek Czajkowski describes the circumstances of the archbishop being invited by Governor [[Hans Frank]] to [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler's]] birthday party in April 1942. He told the German official: ''No! They are not going to change anything, but they will take a photograph of me and write that a Polish bishop arrived at Hitler's birthday party with best wishes. Tell him I will not come.'' Another such anecdote recalls when governor Hans Frank ordered the archbishop to hand him the keys to the [[Wawel Castle]]. Sapieha replied: ''But don't forget to give them back to me when you will be leaving Wawel.''\n\n==Cardinal==\nIn March 1945, he initiated the publication of [[Tygodnik Powszechny]]. He was created [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|Cardinal-Priest]], of the title of ''[[Santa Francesca Romana, Rome|Santa Maria Nuova]]'', on 18 February 1946. On 1 November 1946 he conferred priestly ordination on [[Pope John Paul II|Karol Wojty\u0142a]] in the chapel of his episcopal residence. After the [[Kielce pogrom]] he reportedly stated that the Jews had brought it upon themselves but then provided aid for the affected Jews. According to witness, he and the church complained there were too many Jews in the government. <ref name=\"Kent\">{{cite book|title=The Lonely Cold War of Pope Pius XII: The Roman Catholic Church and the Division of Europe|author=Peter C. Kent|publisher=McGill-Queen's University Press|year=2002|page=128}}<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed & year of publication needed --></ref><Ref>[https://books.google.be/books/content?id=UWJ1Cz8TcRMC&hl=fr&pg=PA138&img=1&zoom=3&sig=ACfU3U3-EG_Cr3WseXKCNmLjlHERLpB9zA&w=1280 Jan Gross(18 d\u00e9c. 2007) Fear: Anti-Semitism in Poland After Auschwitz. Random House Publishing Group p. 138]</ref>\n\nSapieha knew Karol Wojty\u0142a (later John Paul II) was destined to become a priest when a young Karol delivered a welcoming speech during the archbishop's visit to his school. Some people consider him a mentor of [[Pope John Paul II]].{{cn|date=February 2017}} In 1949, he proposed that [[Stefan Wyszy\u0144ski]], [[Archbishop of Gniezno|Metropolitan Archbishop of Gniezno]] and [[List of bishops and archbishops of Warsaw|Warsaw]] since 12 November 1948, should be termed Primate of Poland.{{cn|date=February 2017}} \n\nThe following year (1950), he wrote letters to the then Polish president, [[Boleslaw Bierut]], protesting against Bierut's repression of the church. Sapieha died on 23 July 1951, and his funeral on 28 July turned into a political demonstration. He was buried in [[Wawel Cathedral]], in the crypt under the confessional of [[Stanislaus of Szczepan\u00f3w|St. Stanislas]].{{cn|date=February 2017}}\n\n==Portrayal==\n\nIn the 2005 [[CBS]] [[miniseries]] ''[[Pope John Paul II (miniseries)|Pope John Paul II]]'', Archbishop Sapieha was portrayed by American actor [[James Cromwell]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*St\u0119pie\u0144, Stanis\u0142aw. \"Kardyna\u0142 Adam Stefan Sapieha \u015arodowisko Rodzinne, \u017bycie i Dzie\u0142o\", Przymy\u015bl, 1995 <!-- ISSN/ISBN needed -->\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org Catholic Hierarchy]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080505004723/http://www.icm.com.pl/piotr.boron/prace.php?i=5 Piotr Boron \u2013 Works: Cardinal Stefan Sapieha]\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/024948}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|ca}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Jan Puzyna de Kosielsko]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Bishop of Krak\u00f3w]] | years=24 November 1911\u20131925}}\n{{s-aft | after=Himself'''<br />{{small|''as Archbishop of Krak\u00f3w'''''}}}}\n{{s-bef | before=Himself'''<br />{{small|''as Bishop of Krak\u00f3w'''''}}}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Archbishop of Krak\u00f3w]] | years=1925\u201323 July 1951}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Eugeniusz Baziak]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sapieha, Adam Stefan}}\n[[Category:1867 births]]\n[[Category:1951 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Przemy\u015bl County]]\n[[Category:People from the Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria]]\n[[Category:Sapieha|Adam Stefan]]\n[[Category:Polish cardinals]]\n[[Category:Members of the Diet of Galicia and Lodomeria]]\n[[Category:Senators of the Second Polish Republic (1922\u20131927)]]\n[[Category:Archbishops of Krak\u00f3w]]\n[[Category:Cardinals created by Pope Pius XII]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholic archbishops]]\n[[Category:Jagiellonian University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Vienna alumni]]\n[[Category:Pontifical Gregorian University alumni]]\n[[Category:Burials at Wawel Cathedral]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Christian leader\n| type = Cardinal\n| honorific-prefix = His Eminence \n| name = Adam Stefan Sapieha\n| honorific-suffix = \n| title = [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|Cardinal]], [[Archbishop of Krak\u00f3w]]\n| image = Adam Stefan Sapieha (1867-1951).jpg\n| imagesize = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| church = \n| archdiocese = \n| province = \n| metropolis = \n| diocese = \n| see = \n| elected = \n| appointed = 18 February 1946\n| term_start = 18 February 1946\n| quashed = \n| term_end = 21 July 1951\n| predecessor = [[Jan Puzyna de Kosielsko]]\n| opposed = \n| successor = [[Eugeniusz Baziak]] (apostolic administrator)\n| other_post = Cardinal-Priest of S. Maria Nuova\n<!---------- Orders ---------->\n| ordination = 1 October 1893\n| ordained_by = [[Jan Maurycy Pawel Puzyna de Kosielsko]]\n| consecration = 17 December 1911\n| consecrated_by = [[Pope Pius X]]\n| cardinal = 18 February 1946\n| rank =\n<!---------- Personal details ---------->\n| birth_name = Prince Adam Stefan Stanis\u0142aw Bonfatiusz J\u00f3zef Sapieha\n| birth_date = {{birth date|df=y|1867|5|14}}\n| birth_place = [[Krasiczyn]], [[Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria]], [[Austrian Empire]] (now in Poland)\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=y|1951|7|21|1867|5|14}}\n| death_place = [[Krak\u00f3w]], Poland\n| buried = \n| nationality = Polish\n| religion = [[Roman Catholic]]\n| residence = \n| parents = Adam Stanis\u0142aw Sapieha-Kodenski<br />Jadwiga Klementyna Sanguszko-Lubartowicza\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| alma_mater = \n| motto = \n| coat_of_arms = Card Sapieha COA.png\n<!---------- Sainthood ---------->\n| feast_day = \n| venerated = \n| saint_title = \n| beatified_date = \n| beatified_place = \n| beatified_by = \n| canonized_date = \n| canonized_place = \n| canonized_by = \n| attributes = \n| patronage = \n| shrine = \n| suppressed_date =\n<!---------- Other ---------->\n| other = \n}}\n{{Infobox nobility|type\n| name = Adam Stefan Sapieha \n| CoA = [[Lis coat of arms]] [[File:Herb Sapieh\u00f3w.PNG|150px]]\n| more = no\n| noble family = [[Sapieha]]\n| house-type = Szlachta\n}}\n{{Infobox cardinalstyles\n| cardinal name = Adam Stefan Sapieha\n| image = Card Sapieha COA.png\n| dipstyle = [[His Eminence]]\n| offstyle = Your Eminence\n| relstyle = (autofilled)\n| See = Krak\u00f3w\n}}\n\n'''Prince Adam Stefan Stanis\u0142aw Bonifacy J\u00f3zef Sapieha''' ({{IPA-pl|\u02c8adam \u02c8st\u025bfan sa\u02c8p\u02b2\u025bxa}}; 14 May 1867 \u2013 23 July 1951) was a [[Poland|Polish]] [[cardinal (Catholicism)|cardinal]] of the [[Roman Catholic Church]] who served as [[Archbishop of Krak\u00f3w]]. Between 1922\u20131923 he was a senator of the [[Second Polish Republic]] (Polish ''Rzeczpospolita''). In 1946, [[Pope Pius XII]] created him Cardinal.\n\n==Early life==\nSapieha was born in 1867 in the castle of [[Krasiczyn]], then part of the [[Austrian Empire]]. His family, originally from the [[Grand Duchy of Lithuania]], were members of the Polish [[nobility]]. He was the youngest of the seven children of Prince [[Adam Stanis\u0142aw Sapieha|Adam Stanis\u0142aw Sapieha-Kodenski]] and Princess Jadwiga Klementyna [[House of Sanguszko|Sanguszko-Lubartowicza]], daughter of [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Hieronim Sanguszko]]. His elder brother prince [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw Leon Sapieha]] is the great-grand father of [[Mathilde of Belgium|Queen Mathilde of the Belgians]].\n\n==Education and early vocation==\nAfter graduating from [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]] in [[Lw\u00f3w]] in 1886, he enrolled in the Law Department at the [[University of Vienna]], starting simultaneously law studies at [[Institut Catholique de Paris|Institut Catholique]] in [[Lille]]. In 1887 on the basis of his certificate from the [[University of Vienna]] Sapieha continued studies at the [[Jagiellonian University]] in [[Krak\u00f3w]]. After two years he passed the examination and returned to [[Vienna]] for further studies, where he remained until 1890, obtaining the certificate of completion. \n\nIn the same year he began theological studies at the [[University of Innsbruck]], and in 1892 signed up for the third year of the [[Roman Catholic Seminary in Lviv|Major Roman Catholic Theological Seminary in Lviv]]. He was then educated at the [[Pontifical Gregorian University]] in Rome, where he was also [[Priesthood (Catholic Church)|ordained as priest]] of [[Lviv]] (Lw\u00f3w, Lemberg) on 1 October 1893 by Bishop [[Jan Puzyna de Kosielsko]] (later [[Bishop of Krak\u00f3w]] and Cardinal). Father Sapieha then did pastoral work in the Archdiocese of Lviv before in October 1895 he started further studies in Rome, where he obtained a doctorate of civil and canon law at the [[Pontifical Ecclesiastical Academy]]. At the same time he studied diplomacy at the [[Pontifical Academy of Ecclesiastical Nobles]].\n\nAfter returning to the home country in 1897, he was designated vice-rector of the diocesan seminary in Lviv and eventually became its [[Rector (academia)|rector]]. He resigned because he was discouraged by the imposed rules of education of young priests. After a half-year trip across the [[United states of america|United States of America]], he was designated a vicar of the St. Nicholas congregation in Lviv in October 1902. In 1905 Sapieha was appointed a [[papal chamberlain]], and sent to Rome where he was a consultant on matters concerning the Roman Catholic Church in Poland, in the [[History of Poland|annexed territories]], the realization of an idea by Lviv [[Armenian Catholic]] Archbishop [[J\u00f3zef Teodorowicz]] (who was the Sapieha's long-term friend)<ref>Wielki Zapomniany, ks.Tadeusz Isakowicz-Zaleski. [http://lwow.home.pl/ormianie/teodorowicz.html ks. abp J\u00f3zef Teodorowicz (1864\u20131938)].</ref> to have a representative of the Roman Catholic Church in Poland at the [[Roman Curia]].\n\n==Bishop==\nSapieha was appointed [[Bishop of Krak\u00f3w]] on 24 November 1911 and was consecrated by [[Pope Pius X]] in the [[Sistine Chapel]] on 7 December of the same year. In 1915, he established a relief committee for victims of World War I.\n\nAfter World War I, Sapieha became a vocal opponent of the new [[concordat]] negotiated between the [[Holy See]] and the newly resurrected Polish state. He argued that the Polish Church should be completely independent of the state and that its primate should be the [[Archbishop of Warsaw]]. This attitude led to a conflict with [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|Cardinal]] [[Achille Ratti]], [[Pope Benedict XV]]'s nuncio who himself later became [[Pope]], during the first post-war congress of Polish bishops in [[Gniezno]] held 26\u201330 August 1919. Sapieha thought that the Polish should decide their affairs without outside influence and asked Ratti to leave the conference room. Sapieha was not elevated to the cardinalate by Ratti after he became Pope [[Pius XI]] in 1922.\n\nIn 1922, Sapieha was elected senator from the [[Christian Union of National Unity]] party. He ordered a memorial service and issued a proclamation on the assassination of [[Gabriel Narutowicz]]. It was the only speech he delivered as a senator because papal mandate at the time prohibited clergy from holding public office. He resigned on 9 March 1923.\n\nSapieha was appointed Metropolitan Archbishop in 1925 when the Diocese of Krak\u00f3w was elevated to the rank of Archdiocese. He received a [[honorary degree|degree honoris causa]] from the [[Jagiellonian University]] in 1926. In September 1930, after opposition leaders were arrested and placed in confinement at [[Brest Fortress]], Archbishops Sapieha and Teodorowicz strongly criticized the government. Despite this, and other occasional disagreements with the government, Sapieha was awarded the [[Order of the White Eagle (Poland)|Order of the White Eagle]] in 1936.\n\nIn 1937, Sapieha, who had opposed the [[J\u00f3zef Pi\u0142sudski|Pilsudski]] regime (sanacja), made the controversial decision to move Pi\u0142sudski's body, within [[Wawel Cathedral|Wawel's Cathedral]], from [[St. Leonard's Crypt]] to the crypt under the Silver Bells.<ref>Historical Dictionary of Poland, 966-1945. Jerzy Jan Lerski, 1996.[https://books.google.com/books?id=S6aUBuWPqywC&pg=PA525 Google Print, page 525].</ref><ref>Annual Register, edited by Edmund Burke. [https://books.google.com/books?id=ASoNAAAAIAAJ&dq=sapieha+pilsudski+crypt&q=sacred&pgis=1#search Google Print, page 202].</ref>\n\nIn 1939 he asked [[Pope Pius XI]] to accept his resignation due to age and failing health, but the pope refused. After the death of Pius XI, he repeated his request to the new pope, [[Pius XII]] on 19 June 1939. In anticipation of the upcoming war and at [[J\u00f3zef Beck]]'s instigation he withdrew his resignation.\n\n===Activities during the Second World War===\nDuring World War II, while Primate [[August Hlond]] was in France, Sapieha was the de facto head of the Polish church in jurisdictions directly annexed by the [[Third Reich]] (primate Hlond was represented by Walenty Dymek, auxiliary bishop of Pozna\u0144) and was one of the main leaders of the nation{{Citation needed|date=August 2010}}. One of the most important organisations to which he belonged was the [[National Council of Welfare]], created on the model of [[Caritas (charity)|Caritas]]. From the war's start of the Nazi occupation, he was an independence activist, working with the [[Polish government-in-exile]].\n\nIn August 1944, Sapieha was forced to operate the Polish seminary in secret because the Germans began killing seminarians whenever they found them. He moved his students (including the future [[Pope John Paul II]], Karol Wojty\u0142a) into the [[Bishop's Palace, Krak\u00f3w|Bishop's Palace in Krak\u00f3w]] to finish their training during the Nazi [[Occupation of Poland]].<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7ICFN4iJpgwC&pg=PA280 |title=Social Memory and History: Anthropological perspectives|first1=Jacob J. |last1=Climo|first2=Maria G.|last2=Cattell|year=2002 |publisher=Rowman Altamira|isbn=0759101787|page=280}}</ref>\n\nSapieha's biographer, Jacek Czajkowski describes the circumstances of the archbishop being invited by Governor [[Hans Frank]] to [[Adolf Hitler|Hitler's]] birthday party in April 1942. He told the German official: ''No! They are not going to change anything, but they will take a photograph of me and write that a Polish bishop arrived at Hitler's birthday party with best wishes. Tell him I will not come.'' Another such anecdote recalls when governor Hans Frank ordered the archbishop to hand him the keys to the [[Wawel Castle]]. Sapieha replied: ''But don't forget to give them back to me when you will be leaving Wawel.''\n\n==Cardinal==\nIn March 1945, he initiated the publication of [[Tygodnik Powszechny]]. He was created [[Cardinal (Catholicism)|Cardinal-Priest]], of the title of ''[[Santa Francesca Romana, Rome|Santa Maria Nuova]]'', on 18 February 1946. On 1 November 1946 he conferred priestly ordination on [[Pope John Paul II|Karol Wojty\u0142a]] in the chapel of his episcopal residence. After the [[Kielce pogrom]] he reportedly stated that the Jews had brought it upon themselves but then provided aid for the affected Jews. According to witness, he and the church complained there were too many Jews in the government. <ref name=\"Kent\">{{cite book|title=The Lonely Cold War of Pope Pius XII: The Roman Catholic Church and the Division of Europe|author=Peter C. Kent|publisher=McGill-Queen's University Press|year=2002|page=128}}<!-- ISSN/ISBN needed & year of publication needed --></ref><Ref>[https://books.google.be/books/content?id=UWJ1Cz8TcRMC&hl=fr&pg=PA138&img=1&zoom=3&sig=ACfU3U3-EG_Cr3WseXKCNmLjlHERLpB9zA&w=1280 Jan Gross(18 d\u00e9c. 2007) Fear: Anti-Semitism in Poland After Auschwitz. Random House Publishing Group p. 138]</ref>\n\nSapieha knew Karol Wojty\u0142a (later John Paul II) was destined to become a priest when a young Karol delivered a welcoming speech during the archbishop's visit to his school. Some people consider him a mentor of [[Pope John Paul II]].{{cn|date=February 2017}} In 1949, he proposed that [[Stefan Wyszy\u0144ski]], [[Archbishop of Gniezno|Metropolitan Archbishop of Gniezno]] and [[List of bishops and archbishops of Warsaw|Warsaw]] since 12 November 1948, should be termed Primate of Poland.{{cn|date=February 2017}} \n\nThe following year (1950), he wrote letters to the then Polish president, [[Boleslaw Bierut]], protesting against Bierut's repression of the church. Sapieha died on 23 July 1951, and his funeral on 28 July turned into a political demonstration. He was buried in [[Wawel Cathedral]], in the crypt under the confessional of [[Stanislaus of Szczepan\u00f3w|St. Stanislas]].{{cn|date=February 2017}}\n\n==Portrayal==\n\nIn the 2005 [[CBS]] [[miniseries]] ''[[Pope John Paul II (miniseries)|Pope John Paul II]]'', Archbishop Sapieha was portrayed by American actor [[James Cromwell]].\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*St\u0119pie\u0144, Stanis\u0142aw. \"Kardyna\u0142 Adam Stefan Sapieha \u015arodowisko Rodzinne, \u017bycie i Dzie\u0142o\", Przymy\u015bl, 1995 <!-- ISSN/ISBN needed -->\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org Catholic Hierarchy]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080505004723/http://www.icm.com.pl/piotr.boron/prace.php?i=5 Piotr Boron \u2013 Works: Cardinal Stefan Sapieha]\n* {{PM20|FID=pe/024948}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-rel|ca}}\n{{s-bef | before=[[Jan Puzyna de Kosielsko]]}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Bishop of Krak\u00f3w]] | years=24 November 1911\u20131925}}\n{{s-aft | after=Himself'''<br />{{small|''as Archbishop of Krak\u00f3w'''''}}}}\n{{s-bef | before=Himself'''<br />{{small|''as Bishop of Krak\u00f3w'''''}}}}\n{{s-ttl | title=[[Archbishop of Krak\u00f3w]] | years=1925\u201323 July 1951}}\n{{s-aft | after=[[Eugeniusz Baziak]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sapieha, Adam Stefan}}\n[[Category:1867 births]]\n[[Category:1951 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Przemy\u015bl County]]\n[[Category:People from the Kingdom of Galicia and Lodomeria]]\n[[Category:Sapieha|Adam Stefan]]\n[[Category:Polish cardinals]]\n[[Category:Members of the Diet of Galicia and Lodomeria]]\n[[Category:Senators of the Second Polish Republic (1922\u20131927)]]\n[[Category:Archbishops of Krak\u00f3w]]\n[[Category:Cardinals created by Pope Pius XII]]\n[[Category:20th-century Roman Catholic archbishops]]\n[[Category:Jagiellonian University alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Vienna alumni]]\n[[Category:Pontifical Gregorian University alumni]]\n[[Category:Burials at Wawel Cathedral]]\n", "name_user": "Wbm1058", "label": "safe", "comment": "Spelling correction; redirect bypass fromUnited states of americatoUnited Statesusingpopups", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adam_Stefan_Sapieha"}
{"title_page": "Jeffrey Gettleman", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| image       =\n| name        = Jeffrey Gettleman\n| birthname   = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1971|7|22}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation  = Journalist\n| alias       = \n| title       =  \n| family      = \n| spouse      = Courtenay Morris (m. 2005)\n| children    = \n| relatives   = \n| ethnicity   = \n| religion    = \n| salary      = \n| networth    = \n| credits     = ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', ''[[St. Petersburg Times]]'', ''[[Cherwell (newspaper)|Cherwell]]''\n| URL         = \n| agent       =}}\n'''Jeffrey A. Gettleman''' (born 1971) is an [[Americans|American]] [[Pulitzer prize]]-winning journalist. Since 2018, he has been the [[South Asia]] bureau chief of [[The New York Times]] based in [[New Delhi]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/by/jeffrey-gettleman|title=Jeffrey Gettleman|date=2019-07-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>  From 2006-July 2017, he was East Africa bureau chief for ''The Times''.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/27/insider/romance-war-survival-a-correspondent-looks-back-on-his-experience-in-east-africa.html?action=click&pgtype=Homepage&module=timesinsider&region=c-column-bottom-span-region Gettleman looks bac]</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\n===Personal life===\nJeffrey was born in 1971, the son of [[Robert William Gettleman]] (b. 1943),<ref>[http://www.ilnd.uscourts.gov/JUDGE/GETTLEMAN/RWGBio.htm Biographical data for Judge Robert W. Gettleman - United State District Court for the Northern District of Illinois.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917163811/http://www.ilnd.uscourts.gov/Judge/GETTLEMAN/RWGBio.htm |date=2008-09-17 }} Accessed 18 May 2007.</ref> a judge of the United State District Court for the Northern District of [[Illinois]],<ref>[http://www.ibiblio.org/pub/archives/whitehouse-papers/1994/Aug/1994-08-16-President-Names-Four-to-Federal-Bench-in-Illinois The White House Office of the Press Secretary press release, dated 16 August 1994.]</ref> and Joyce R. Gettleman, a psychotherapist with a private practice in [[Evanston, Illinois|Evanston]].<ref>[http://home.datacomm.ch/rezamusic/HonorableGettleman.html Interview with Honorable Judge Robert W. Gettleman] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120711002716/http://home.datacomm.ch/rezamusic/HonorableGettleman.html |date=2012-07-11 }}</ref> Gettleman's sister Lynn Gettleman Chehab is a physician.\n\nGettleman is married to Courtenay Morris,<ref name=\"Kelly Award\"/> a former assistant [[public defender]] who is now a web producer for the ''Times''. The couple first met while both were attending [[Cornell University]]. The wedding was held on October 29, 2005 at their home in [[Hoboken, New Jersey|Hoboken]], [[New Jersey]], with Gettleman's father officiating at the ceremony.<ref name=\"Ncmajg\">{{cite news|title=Courtenay Morris and Jeffrey Gettleman|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/10/30/fashion/weddings/30MORR.html|accessdate=14 July 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=30 October 2005}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nGettleman graduated from [[Evanston Township High School]] in 1989, and Cornell University in 1994 with a B.A. in Philosophy.<ref name=\"nytaskareporter\">[https://www.nytimes.com/learning/students/ask_reporters/Jeffrey_Gettleman.html ''The New York Times'' Ask a Reporter Q&A: Jeffrey Gettleman]</ref> Initially, he did not know what he wanted to do after graduation, so took a leave of absence to back pack around the world which he says help set his life trajectory. However, when a professor suggested journalism as a profession, he scoffed at the idea, saying \"That was the dumbest idea I had heard... who wants to work for a boring newspaper?\".<ref name=\"Cornell Sun\">{{cite web|url=http://cornellsun.com/node/46653 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130120074501/http://cornellsun.com/node/46653 |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 20, 2013 |title=New York Times Reporter Jeffrey Gettleman '94 Chronicles His Time in Africa |author=Max Schindler |date=April 6, 2011 |access-date=November 30, 2011 }}</ref> Beginning in 1994, he was a communications officer for the [[Save the Children]] organization in [[Addis Ababa]].\n\nAfter his graduation from Cornell, Gettleman received a [[Marshall Scholarship]] to attend [[Oxford University]], where he received a master's degree in Philosophy in June 1996. While at Oxford, he was the first American editor of ''[[Cherwell (newspaper)|Cherwell]]'', the university's student newspaper.<ref name=\"Kelly Award\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kellyaward.com/mk_award_popup/gettleman_j.html |title=The Michael Kelly Award 2012 |publisher=Atlantic Media Company |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110819091501/http://kellyaward.com/mk_award_popup/gettleman_j.html |archive-date=2011-08-19 |df= }}</ref><ref>http://www.cherwell.org/comment/world/2013/01/26/interview-jeffrey-gettleman</ref>\n\n==Career==\nGettleman began his journalism career as a city hall and police reporter for the ''[[St. Petersburg Times]]'' from 1997\u20131998. In 1999, he transferred to the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' as a general assignment reporter. He became bureau chief in [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]] two years later, and was also a war correspondent for the broadsheet in [[Afghanistan]] and the [[Middle East]].\n\nIn 2002, Gettleman joined ''The New York Times'' as a domestic correspondent in Atlanta, where he later became the bureau chief. He reported from [[Iraq]] beginning in 2003, where he did a total of five tours. After a stint as a reporter for the paper's Metro desk in 2004, he became a foreign correspondent in July 2006 for the [[Nairobi]]-based East Africa bureau of The New York Times. Only a month later, he would be named chief.<ref name=\"Kelly Award\"/>\n\nCurrently, Gettleman covers over ten countries, often under difficult circumstances. He has focused the majority of his work on events in [[Republic of the Congo|Congo]], [[Kenya]] and [[Tanzania]] in [[East Africa|East]]-[[Central Africa]], where he has reported on atrocities involving rape, mutilation as well as ritualized murders of [[albino]]s, among other issues. His often straightforward, non-cynical approach toward such difficult stories has been colloquially dubbed the \"Gettleman method\" by [[Jack Shafer]].<ref name=\"Cornell Sun\"/><ref name=\"Shafer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/press_box/2009/03/jeffrey_gettlemans_world_of_war.html|title=Jeffrey Gettleman's World of War|author=Jack Shafer|date=March 4, 2009|accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wesleyanargus.com/2004/10/26/ny-times-correspondent-in-iraq-discusses-experience-as-hostage/|title=NY Times correspondent in Iraq discusses experience as hostage|author=Sacha Feinman|date=October 26, 2004|accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nGettleman has also covered conflicts in [[Sudan]], [[Ethiopia]], [[Somalia]], [[Egypt]] and [[Yemen]]. In the 2004 spring, he along with photographer Lynsey Addario were abducted for several hours by militants in [[Fallujah]]. According to Gettleman, the pair were eventually released because he had successfully posed as [[Greek people|Greek]] and concealed his passport in Addario's trousers, where he had guessed his captors would not search.<ref name=\"Shafer\"/>\n\nIn addition, Gettleman has served as a commentator on [[CNN]], [[BBC]], [[PBS]], [[NPR]] and [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/g/jeffrey_gettleman/index.html?scp=1-spot&sq=Jeffrey%20Gettleman&st=cse|website=The New York Times|title=Jeffrey Gettleman}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Gettlemen published his memoir, Love, ''Africa: A Memoir of Romance, War, and Survival''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/03/books/review/love-africa-memoir-jeffrey-gettleman.html|title=Stories of a Lifelong Fascination With Africa|last=Mohamed|first=Nadifa|date=2017-07-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* First place for general reporting by Florida Press Club (1997)\n* First place for spot news by Tampa Bay Society of Professional Journalists (1997 and 1998)\n* ''Los Angeles Times'' Editorial Award for Breaking News (2001)\n* Overseas Press Club Award (2003)\n* Overseas Press Club Award (2008)\n* [[George Polk Award]] for International Reporting (2011)<ref>{{cite web|title=Jeffrey Gettleman: On Reporting Somalia's Crisis|website=[[NPR]]|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/04/04/149390748/jeffrey-gettleman-on-reporting-somalias-crisis|date=March 26, 2012|access-date=January 28, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Pulitzer Prize for International Reporting]] (2012)<ref>[http://www.pulitzer.org/citation/2012-International-Reporting The 2012 Pulitzer Prize Winners - International Reporting]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|Jeffrey Gettleman}}\n\n{{PulitzerPrize International Reporting}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gettleman, Jeffrey}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Balliol College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Times people]]\n[[Category:The New York Times writers]]\n[[Category:Marshall Scholars]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Pulitzer Prize for International Reporting winners]]\n[[Category:Writers from Evanston, Illinois]]\n[[Category:George Polk Award recipients]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| image       =\n| name        = Jeffrey Gettleman\n| birthname   = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1971|7|22}}\n| birth_place = \n| death_date  = \n| death_place = \n| occupation  = Journalist\n| alias       = \n| title       =  \n| family      = \n| spouse      = Courtenay Morris (m. 2005)\n| children    = \n| relatives   = \n| ethnicity   = \n| religion    = \n| salary      = \n| networth    = \n| credits     = ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', ''[[St. Petersburg Times]]'', ''[[Cherwell (newspaper)|Cherwell]]''\n| URL         = \n| agent       =}}\n'''Jeffrey A. Gettleman''' (born 1971) is an [[Americans|American]] [[Pulitzer prize]]-winning journalist. Since 2018, he has been the [[South Asia]] bureau chief of [[The New York Times]] based in [[New Delhi]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/by/jeffrey-gettleman|title=Jeffrey Gettleman|date=2019-07-14|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-14|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>  From 2006-July 2017, he was the ''The Times'' East Africa Bureau Chief.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/27/insider/romance-war-survival-a-correspondent-looks-back-on-his-experience-in-east-africa.html?action=click&pgtype=Homepage&module=timesinsider&region=c-column-bottom-span-region Gettleman looks bac]</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\n===Personal life===\nJeffrey was born in 1971, the son of [[Robert William Gettleman]] (b. 1943),<ref>[http://www.ilnd.uscourts.gov/JUDGE/GETTLEMAN/RWGBio.htm Biographical data for Judge Robert W. Gettleman - United State District Court for the Northern District of Illinois.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080917163811/http://www.ilnd.uscourts.gov/Judge/GETTLEMAN/RWGBio.htm |date=2008-09-17 }} Accessed 18 May 2007.</ref> a judge of the United State District Court for the Northern District of [[Illinois]],<ref>[http://www.ibiblio.org/pub/archives/whitehouse-papers/1994/Aug/1994-08-16-President-Names-Four-to-Federal-Bench-in-Illinois The White House Office of the Press Secretary press release, dated 16 August 1994.]</ref> and Joyce R. Gettleman, a psychotherapist with a private practice in [[Evanston, Illinois|Evanston]].<ref>[http://home.datacomm.ch/rezamusic/HonorableGettleman.html Interview with Honorable Judge Robert W. Gettleman] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120711002716/http://home.datacomm.ch/rezamusic/HonorableGettleman.html |date=2012-07-11 }}</ref> Gettleman's sister Lynn Gettleman Chehab is a physician.\n\nGettleman is married to Courtenay Morris,<ref name=\"Kelly Award\"/> a former assistant [[public defender]] who is now a web producer for the ''Times''. The couple first met while both were attending [[Cornell University]]. The wedding was held on October 29, 2005 at their home in [[Hoboken, New Jersey|Hoboken]], [[New Jersey]], with Gettleman's father officiating at the ceremony.<ref name=\"Ncmajg\">{{cite news|title=Courtenay Morris and Jeffrey Gettleman|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/10/30/fashion/weddings/30MORR.html|accessdate=14 July 2012|newspaper=New York Times|date=30 October 2005}}</ref>\n\n===Education===\nGettleman graduated from [[Evanston Township High School]] in 1989, and Cornell University in 1994 with a B.A. in Philosophy.<ref name=\"nytaskareporter\">[https://www.nytimes.com/learning/students/ask_reporters/Jeffrey_Gettleman.html ''The New York Times'' Ask a Reporter Q&A: Jeffrey Gettleman]</ref> Initially, he did not know what he wanted to do after graduation, so took a leave of absence to back pack around the world which he says help set his life trajectory. However, when a professor suggested journalism as a profession, he scoffed at the idea, saying \"That was the dumbest idea I had heard... who wants to work for a boring newspaper?\".<ref name=\"Cornell Sun\">{{cite web|url=http://cornellsun.com/node/46653 |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130120074501/http://cornellsun.com/node/46653 |url-status=dead |archive-date=January 20, 2013 |title=New York Times Reporter Jeffrey Gettleman '94 Chronicles His Time in Africa |author=Max Schindler |date=April 6, 2011 |access-date=November 30, 2011 }}</ref> Beginning in 1994, he was a communications officer for the [[Save the Children]] organization in [[Addis Ababa]].\n\nAfter his graduation from Cornell, Gettleman received a [[Marshall Scholarship]] to attend [[Oxford University]], where he received a master's degree in Philosophy in June 1996. While at Oxford, he was the first American editor of ''[[Cherwell (newspaper)|Cherwell]]'', the university's student newspaper.<ref name=\"Kelly Award\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kellyaward.com/mk_award_popup/gettleman_j.html |title=The Michael Kelly Award 2012 |publisher=Atlantic Media Company |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110819091501/http://kellyaward.com/mk_award_popup/gettleman_j.html |archive-date=2011-08-19 |df= }}</ref><ref>http://www.cherwell.org/comment/world/2013/01/26/interview-jeffrey-gettleman</ref>\n\n==Career==\nGettleman began his journalism career as a city hall and police reporter for the ''[[St. Petersburg Times]]'' from 1997\u20131998. In 1999, he transferred to the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' as a general assignment reporter. He became bureau chief in [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]] two years later, and was also a war correspondent for the broadsheet in [[Afghanistan]] and the [[Middle East]].\n\nIn 2002, Gettleman joined ''The New York Times'' as a domestic correspondent in Atlanta, where he later became the bureau chief. He reported from [[Iraq]] beginning in 2003, where he did a total of five tours. After a stint as a reporter for the paper's Metro desk in 2004, he became a foreign correspondent in July 2006 for the [[Nairobi]]-based East Africa bureau of The New York Times. Only a month later, he would be named chief.<ref name=\"Kelly Award\"/>\n\nCurrently, Gettleman covers over ten countries, often under difficult circumstances. He has focused the majority of his work on events in [[Republic of the Congo|Congo]], [[Kenya]] and [[Tanzania]] in [[East Africa|East]]-[[Central Africa]], where he has reported on atrocities involving rape, mutilation as well as ritualized murders of [[albino]]s, among other issues. His often straightforward, non-cynical approach toward such difficult stories has been colloquially dubbed the \"Gettleman method\" by [[Jack Shafer]].<ref name=\"Cornell Sun\"/><ref name=\"Shafer\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/press_box/2009/03/jeffrey_gettlemans_world_of_war.html|title=Jeffrey Gettleman's World of War|author=Jack Shafer|date=March 4, 2009|accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://wesleyanargus.com/2004/10/26/ny-times-correspondent-in-iraq-discusses-experience-as-hostage/|title=NY Times correspondent in Iraq discusses experience as hostage|author=Sacha Feinman|date=October 26, 2004|accessdate=November 30, 2011}}</ref>\n\nGettleman has also covered conflicts in [[Sudan]], [[Ethiopia]], [[Somalia]], [[Egypt]] and [[Yemen]]. In the 2004 spring, he along with photographer Lynsey Addario were abducted for several hours by militants in [[Fallujah]]. According to Gettleman, the pair were eventually released because he had successfully posed as [[Greek people|Greek]] and concealed his passport in Addario's trousers, where he had guessed his captors would not search.<ref name=\"Shafer\"/>\n\nIn addition, Gettleman has served as a commentator on [[CNN]], [[BBC]], [[PBS]], [[NPR]] and [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/g/jeffrey_gettleman/index.html?scp=1-spot&sq=Jeffrey%20Gettleman&st=cse|website=The New York Times|title=Jeffrey Gettleman}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Gettlemen published his memoir, Love, ''Africa: A Memoir of Romance, War, and Survival''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/03/books/review/love-africa-memoir-jeffrey-gettleman.html|title=Stories of a Lifelong Fascination With Africa|last=Mohamed|first=Nadifa|date=2017-07-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-07-12|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n* First place for general reporting by Florida Press Club (1997)\n* First place for spot news by Tampa Bay Society of Professional Journalists (1997 and 1998)\n* ''Los Angeles Times'' Editorial Award for Breaking News (2001)\n* Overseas Press Club Award (2003)\n* Overseas Press Club Award (2008)\n* [[George Polk Award]] for International Reporting (2011)<ref>{{cite web|title=Jeffrey Gettleman: On Reporting Somalia's Crisis|website=[[NPR]]|url=https://www.npr.org/2012/04/04/149390748/jeffrey-gettleman-on-reporting-somalias-crisis|date=March 26, 2012|access-date=January 28, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Pulitzer Prize for International Reporting]] (2012)<ref>[http://www.pulitzer.org/citation/2012-International-Reporting The 2012 Pulitzer Prize Winners - International Reporting]</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{C-SPAN|Jeffrey Gettleman}}\n\n{{PulitzerPrize International Reporting}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gettleman, Jeffrey}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Balliol College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Times people]]\n[[Category:The New York Times writers]]\n[[Category:Marshall Scholars]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Pulitzer Prize for International Reporting winners]]\n[[Category:Writers from Evanston, Illinois]]\n[[Category:George Polk Award recipients]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Typo fixing, replaced: the ''The  \u2192  ''The", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeffrey_Gettleman"}
{"title_page": "Old Persian cuneiform", "text_new": "{{Short description|semi-alphabetic cuneiform script}}\n{{Infobox Writing system\n |name=Old Persian Cuneiform\n |type=[[Semisyllabary]]\n |languages=[[Old Persian]]\n |time=525 BC \u2013 330 BC\n |fam1=none; apparently inspired by [[Cuneiform script]]\n |unicode=[https://www.unicode.org/charts/PDF/U103A0.pdf U+103A0&ndash;U+103D5]\n\n[http://www.fontspace.com/fereydoun/behistun Download \"Behistun\"], a free Old Persian Cuneiform Unicode font, install and refresh the page.\n\nIf you don't use Firefox or Opera, see [https://www.unicode.org/help/display_problems.html#Browsers the attached page] to configure your browser's encoding to Unicode.\n\n |iso15924=Xpeo\n |sample=\n{{multiple image|perrow=2|total_width=300|caption_align=center\n| align    = center\n| direction =horizontal\n| image1   = Old Persian cuneiform.jpg\n| image2   = Tomb of Darius I DNa inscription part II.jpg\n}}\n|caption=Old Persian cuneiform syllabary (left), and the [[DNa inscription]] (part II, right) of [[Darius the Great]] (circa 490 BC), in the newly created script.\n |imagesize=300\n}}\n[[File:Old Persian for King.jpg|thumb|300px|This Old Persian cuneiform word, because of its numerous occurrences in  inscriptions, was correctly guessed as being the word for \"King\". The words positionned before it would then logically be the names of kings, which were known historically from other sources. Various characteristics of these words, such as length or recurrence of signs, allowed to discriminate between the various possible kings, and then create a correspondence between each cuneiform and a specific sound. This word is now known to be pronounced ''x\u0161\u0101ya\u03d1iya'' (\ud800\udfa7\ud800\udfc1\ud800\udfa0\ud800\udfb9\ud800\udfb0\ud800\udfa1\ud800\udfb9), and indeed means \"King\".<ref name=\"RGK\"/>]]\n'''Old Persian cuneiform''' is a semi-alphabetic [[cuneiform script]] that was the primary script for [[Old Persian]].  Texts written in this cuneiform have been found in [[Iran]] ([[Persepolis]], [[Susa]], [[Hamadan]], [[Kharg Island]]), [[Armenia]], [[Romania]] ([[Gherla]]),{{sfn|Kuhrt|2013|page=197}}{{sfn|Frye|1984|page=103}}{{sfn|Schmitt|2000|page=53}} [[Turkey]] ([[Van Fortress]]), and along the [[Suez Canal]].<ref name=\"OPGTL 6\">Kent, R. G.: \"Old Persian: Grammar Texts Lexicon\", page 6. American Oriental Society, 1950.</ref> They were mostly inscriptions from the time period of [[Darius I]], such as the [[DNa inscription]], as well as his son, [[Xerxes I]].<ref name=\"OLDPERSIANDICTIONARY\">Bachenheimer, Avi: \"Old Persian: Dictionary, Glossary and Concordance\", pages 27-92.</ref> Later kings down to [[Artaxerxes III]] used more recent forms of the language classified as \"pre-Middle Persian\".<ref name=\"OPGTL 6\" />\n\n==History==\nOld Persian cuneiform is loosely inspired by the [[Sumerian language|Sumero]]-[[Akkadian language|Akkadian]] [[Cuneiform script|cuneiform]]; however, only one [[glyph]] is directly derived from it - ''l(a)'' ({{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfbe}}), from ''la'' ({{cuneiform|\ud808\uddb7}}). (''l<sup>a</sup>'' did not occur in native Old Persian words, but was found in Akkadian borrowings.)\n\nScholars today mostly agree that the Old Persian script was invented by about 525 BC to provide monument inscriptions for the [[Achaemenid]] king [[Darius I of Persia|Darius I]], to be used at [[Behistun]]. While a few Old Persian texts seem to be inscribed during the reigns of [[Cyrus the Great]] (CMa, CMb, and CMc, all found at [[Pasargadae]]), the first Achaemenid emperor, or [[Arsames of Persia|Arsames]] and [[Ariaramnes of Persia|Ariaramnes]] (AsH and AmH, both found at [[Hamadan]]), grandfather and great-grandfather of Darius I, all five, specially the later two, are generally agreed to have been later inscriptions.\n\nAround the time period in which Old Persian was used, nearby languages included [[Elamite]] and [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]].  One of the main differences between the writing systems of these languages is that Old Persian is a semi-alphabet while [[Elamite cuneiform|Elamite]] and [[Cuneiform script#Akkadian cuneiform|Akkadian]] were syllabic. In addition, while Old Persian is written in a consistent semi-alphabetic system, Elamite and Akkadian used borrowings from other languages, creating mixed systems.\n\n==Decipherment==\nMuch of the progress made in [[decipherment]] depended on the names of kings.  Attempts at deciphering Old Persian cuneiform started in 1711 when some of Darius's inscriptions were published by [[Jean Chardin]].<ref name=\"OPGTL 9\">Kent, R. G.: \"Old Persian: Grammar Texts Lexicon\", page 9. American Oriental Society, 1950.</ref> In 1802, [[Friedrich M\u00fcnter]] realized that recurring groups of characters must be the word for \u201cking\u201d ({{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfa7\ud800\udfc1\ud800\udfa0\ud800\udfb9\ud800\udfb0\ud800\udfa1\ud800\udfb9}}, now known to be pronounced ''x\u0161\u0101ya\u03d1iya''). [[Georg Friedrich Grotefend]] extended this work by realizing a king's name is often followed by \u201cgreat king, king of kings\u201d and the name of the king's father.<ref name=\"RGK\">Kent, R. G.: \"Old Persian: Grammar Texts Lexicon\", page 10. American Oriental Society, 1950.</ref>\n\nGrotefend made a major breakthrough when he noticed that one of the kings' father was not a king.  In Persian history around the time period the inscriptions were expected to be made, there were only two instances where a ruler came to power without being a previous king's son.  They were [[Darius the Great]] and [[Cyrus the Great]], both of whom became emperor by revolt. The deciding factors between these two choices were the names of their fathers and sons. Darius's father was Hystaspes and his son was [[Xerxes I of Persia|Xerxes]], while Cyrus' father was [[Cambyses I]] and his son was [[Cambyses II]]. Within the text, the father and son of the king had different groups of symbols for names so Grotefend assumed that the king must have been Darius. These connections allowed Grotefend to figure out the cuneiform characters that are part of Darius, Darius's father Hystaspes, and Darius's son [[Xerxes I of Persia|Xerxes]]. Grotefend's contribution to Old Persian is unique in that he did not have comparisons between Old Persian and known languages, as opposed to the decipherment of the Egyptian hieroglyphics and the [[Rosetta Stone]]. All his decipherments were done by comparing the texts with known history.\n\nMore advances were made on Grotefend's work and by 1847, most of the symbols were correctly identified.  Notable uses of Old Persian's decipherment include the decipherment of Elamite and Akkadian through the [[Behistun Inscription]].\n\n==Signs==\nMost scholars consider the writing system to be an independent invention because it has no obvious connections with other writing systems at the time, such as [[Elamite language|Elamite]], Akkadian, [[Hurrian language|Hurrian]], and [[Hittite language|Hittite]] cuneiforms.<ref>Windfuhr, G. L.: \"Notes on the old Persian signs\", page 1. Indo-Iranian Journal, 1970.</ref> While Old Persian's basic strokes are similar to those found in cuneiform scripts, Old Persian texts were engraved on hard materials, so the engravers had to make cuts that imitated the forms easily made on clay tablets.<ref name=\"OPGTL 9\" />  The signs are composed of horizontal, vertical, and angled wedges.  There are four basic components and new signs are created by adding wedges to these basic components.<ref name=\"NOPS 2\">Windfuhr, G. L.: \"Notes on the old Persian signs\", page 2. Indo-Iranian Journal, 1970.</ref> These four basic components are two parallel wedges without angle, three parallel wedges without angle, one wedge without angle and an angled wedge, and two angled wedges.<ref name=\"NOPS 2\" /> The script is written from left to right.<ref>Daniels, Peter T.: \"The World's Writing Systems\", page 134. Oxford University Press, 1996</ref>\n\n[[File:DNa Inscription D\u0101rayavau\u0161.jpg|thumb|<center>The name of [[Darius I]] in Old Persian cuneiform on the [[DNa inscription]] of [[Tomb of Darius I|his tomb]]: ''D\u0101rayavau\u0161'' ([[Wikt:\ud800\udfad\ud800\udfa0\ud800\udfbc\ud800\udfb9\ud800\udfba\ud800\udfa2\ud800\udfc1|{{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfad\ud800\udfa0\ud800\udfbc\ud800\udfb9\ud800\udfba\ud800\udfa2\ud800\udfc1}}]])</center>]]\nThe script encodes three vowels, ''a'', ''i'', ''u'', and twenty-two consonants, ''k'', ''x'', ''g'', ''c'', ''\u00e7'', ''j'', ''t'', ''\u03b8'', ''d'', ''p'', ''f'', ''b'', ''n'', ''m'', ''y'', ''v'', ''r'', ''l'', ''s'', ''z'', ''\u0161'', and ''h''.  Old Persian contains two sets of consonants: those whose shape depends on the following vowel and those whose shape is independent of the following vowel.  The consonant symbols that depend on the following vowel act like the consonants in [[Devanagari]].  Vowel diacritics are added to these consonant symbols to change the inherent vowel or add length to the inherent vowel.  However, the vowel symbols are usually still included so [di] would be written as [di] [i] even though [di] already implies the vowel.<ref>Daniels, Peter T.: \"The World's Writing Systems\", page 136. Oxford University Press, 1996</ref> For the consonants whose shape does not depend on the following vowels, the vowel signs must be used after the consonant symbol.<ref>Daniels, Peter T.: \"The World's Writing Systems\", page 135. Oxford University Press, 1996</ref>\n\nCompared to the [[Avestan alphabet]] Old Persian notably lacks voiced fricatives, but includes the sign ''\u00e7'' (of uncertain pronunciation) and a sign for the non-native ''l''. Notably, in common with the [[Brahmic scripts]], there appears to be no distinction between a consonant followed by an ''a'' and a consonant followed by nothing.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|  ||  || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">k-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">x-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">g-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">c-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">\u00e7-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">j-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">t-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">\u03b8-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">d-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">p-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">f-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">b-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">n-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">m-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">y-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">v-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">r-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">l-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">s-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">z-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">\u0161-</span> || <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">h-</span>\n|-\n| <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">-(a)</span> || {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfa0}} || {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfa3}} || rowspan=3|{{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfa7}} || {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfa5}} || rowspan=3|{{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfa8}} || rowspan=3|{{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfc2}} || {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfa9}}  || rowspan=2|{{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfab}} || rowspan=3|{{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfb0}} || {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfad}} || rowspan=3|{{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfb1}} || rowspan=3|{{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfb3}} || rowspan=3|{{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfb2}} || rowspan=2|{{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfb4}} || {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfb6}} || rowspan=3|{{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfb9}} || {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfba}} || rowspan=2|{{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfbc}} || rowspan=3|{{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfbe}} || rowspan=3|{{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfbf}} || rowspan=3|{{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfc0}} || rowspan=3|{{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfc1}} || rowspan=3|{{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfc3}}\n|-\n| <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">-i</span> || {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfa1}}\n! <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">\u2014</span> !! \u2014 \n| {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfaa}} || {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfae}} || {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfb7}} || {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfbb}}\n|-\n| <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">-u</span> || {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfa2}} || {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfa4}} || {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfa6}}\n! \u2014\n| {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfac}} || {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfaf}} || {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfb5}} || {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfb8}}\n! \u2014 \n| {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfbd}}\n|-\n|}\n\n*logograms:\n**''[[Ahura Mazda|Auramazd\u0101]]'': {{script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfc8}}, {{script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfc9}}, {{script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfca}} (genitive)\n**''<span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">x\u0161\u0101ya\u03b8iya</span>'' \"king\": {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfcb}}\n**''<span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">dahy\u0101u\u0161-</span>'' \"country\": <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">{{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfcc}}, {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfcd}}</span>\n**''<span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">baga-</span>'' \"god\": {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfce}}\n**''<span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">b\u016bmi\u0161-</span>'' \"earth\": {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfcf}}\n*[[word divider]]: <span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">{{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd0}}</span>\n*numerals:<ref>Unattested numbers are not listed. The list of attested numbers is based on {{cite book|last=Kent|first=Ronald Grubb|others=translated into Persian by S. Oryan|title=Old Persian: Grammar, Text, Glossary|isbn=964-421-045-X|edition=1384 [[Iranian calendar|AP]]|language=Persian|pages=699&ndash;700|publisher=Pizh\u016bhishkadah-i Zab\u0101n va G\u016byish b\u0101 hamk\u0101r\u012b-i Id\u0101rah-i Kull-i Um\u016br-i Farhang\u012b|location=Tihr\u0101n}}\n</ref>\n**<span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">1 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd1}}, 2 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd2}}, 5 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd1}}, 7 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd1}}, 8 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2}}, 9 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd1}}</span>\n**10 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd3}}, 12 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd3\ud800\udfd2}}, 13 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd3\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd1}}, 14 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd3\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2}}, 15 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd3\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd1}}, 18 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd3\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2}}, 19 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd3\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd1}}, 20 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd4}}, 22 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd4\ud800\udfd2}}, 23 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd4\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd1}}, 25 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd4\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd1}}, 26 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd4\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2}}, 27 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd4\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd2\ud800\udfd1}}, 40 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd4\ud800\udfd4}}, 60 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd4\ud800\udfd4\ud800\udfd4}},\n**<span lang=\"peo\" dir=\"ltr\">120 {{script|XPeo|\ud800\udfd5\ud800\udfd4}}</span>\n\n==Alphabetic properties==\n[[File:BehistunInscriptiondetail.jpg|250px|thumb|right|Close-up of the [[Behistun inscription]]]]\n[[File:Pers\u00e9polis. Inscription.jpg|thumb|right|250px|An Old Persian inscription in [[Persepolis]]]]\nAlthough based on a logo-syllabic prototype, all vowels but short /a/ are written and so the system is essentially an [[alphabet]]. There are three vowels, long and short. Initially, no distinction is made for length: {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfa0}} ''a'' or ''\u0101,'' {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfa1}} ''i'' or ''\u012b,'' {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfa2}} ''u'' or ''\u016b.'' However, as in the Brahmic scripts, short ''a'' is not written after a consonant: {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfc3}} ''h'' or ''ha,'' {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfc3\ud800\udfa0}} ''h\u0101,'' {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfc3\ud800\udfa1}} ''hi'' or ''h\u012b,'' {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfc3\ud800\udfa2}} ''hu'' or ''h\u016b.'' (Old Persian is not considered an [[abugida]] because vowels are represented as full letters.)\n\nThirteen out of twenty-two consonants, such as {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfc3}} ''h(a),'' are invariant, regardless of the following vowel (that is, they are alphabetic), while only six have a distinct form for each consonant-vowel combination (that is, they are syllabic), and among these, only ''d'' and ''m'' occur in three forms for all three vowels: {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfad}} ''d'' or ''da,'' {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfad\ud800\udfa0}} ''d\u0101,'' {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfae\ud800\udfa1}} ''di'' or ''d\u012b,'' {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfaf\ud800\udfa2}} ''du'' or ''d\u016b.'' (''k, g'' do not occur before ''i,'' and ''j, v'' do not occur before ''u,'' so these consonants only have two forms each.)\n\nSometimes medial long vowels are written with a ''y'' or ''v,'' as in Semitic: {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfae\ud800\udfa1\ud800\udfb9}} ''d\u012b,'' {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfaf\ud800\udfa2\ud800\udfba}} ''d\u016b.'' Diphthongs are written by mismatching consonant and vowel: {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfad\ud800\udfa1}} ''dai'', or sometimes, in cases where the consonant does not differentiate between vowels, by writing the consonant and both vowel components: {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfa8\ud800\udfa1\ud800\udfc1\ud800\udfb1\ud800\udfa0\ud800\udfa1\ud800\udfc1}} ''ci\u0161pai\u0161'' (gen. of name Ci\u0161pi- '[[Teispes]]').\n\nIn addition, three consonants, ''t'', ''n'', and ''r'', are partially syllabic, having the same form before ''a'' and ''i'', and a distinct form only before ''u'': {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfb4}} ''n'' or ''na,'' {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfb4\ud800\udfa0}} ''n\u0101,'' {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfb4\ud800\udfa1}} ''ni'' or ''n\u012b,'' {{Script|Xpeo|\ud800\udfb5\ud800\udfa2}} ''nu'' or ''n\u016b.''\n\nThe effect is not unlike the English {{IPA|[d\u0292]}} sound, which is typically written ''g'' before ''i'' or ''e'', but ''j'' before other vowels (''gem'', ''jam''), or the [[Castilian Spanish]] {{IPA|[\u03b8]}} sound, which is written ''c'' before ''i'' or ''e'' and ''z'' before other vowels (''cinco, zapato''): it is more accurate to say that some of the Old Persian consonants are written by different letters depending on the following vowel, rather than classifying the script as syllabic. This situation had its origin in [[Cuneiform script#Assyrian cuneiform|Assyrian cuneiform]], where several syllabic distinctions had been lost and were often clarified with explicit vowels. However, in the case of Assyrian, the vowel was not always used, and was never used where not needed, so the system remained (logo-)syllabic.\n\nFor a while it was speculated that the alphabet could have had its origin in such a system, with a leveling of consonant signs a millennium earlier producing something like the [[Ugaritic alphabet]], but today it is generally accepted that the Semitic alphabet arose from [[Egyptian hieroglyphs]], where vowel notation was not important. (See [[Proto-Sinaitic script]].)\n\n==Unicode==\n\n{{Main|Old Persian (Unicode block)}}\n\nOld Persian cuneiform was added to the [[Unicode]] Standard in March 2005 with the release of version 4.1.\n\nThe Unicode block for Old Persian cuneiform is U+103A0&ndash;U+103DF and is in the [[Supplementary Multilingual Plane]]:\n\n{{Unicode chart Old Persian|Old Persian Cuneiform Unicode Font Download = http://www.fontspace.com/download/22120/bdca919040e54ed8aed4b0b525902023/fereydoun_behistun.zip}}\n\n==Notes and references==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite journal\n  | last = Windfuhr\n  | first = Gernot L\n  | authorlink = \n  | title = Notes on the old Persian signs\n  | journal = Indo-Iranian Journal\n  | volume = \n  | issue = 12\n  | pages = 121\u2013125\n  | publisher = \n  | year = 1970\n  | hdl = 2027.42/42943\n  | doi =}}\n*{{cite book\n  | last = Daniels\n  | first = Peter T\n  | authorlink = \n  |author2=William Bright\n  | title = The World's Writing Systems\n  | publisher = Oxford University Press\n  | year = 1996\n  | location = New York\n  | pages = 134\u2013137\n  | url = \n  | doi = \n  | isbn = }}\n*{{cite 