om the Persepolis Fortification Archive Project, 1: An Old Persian Administrative Tablet from the Persepolis Fortification|year=1995|title=Arta|volume=2007:1|location=Paris|publisher=Achemenet.com|last=Stolper|first=Matthew W. & Jan Tavernier|chapter-url=http://persepolistablets.blogspot.com/2007/06/old-persian-text-in-persepolis.html|postscript=<!--None-->}}\n\n===Descriptions===\n*[http://www.omniglot.com/writing/opcuneiform.htm Omniglot article on Old Persian cuneiform]\n*[http://www.ancientscripts.com/oldpersian.html Ancient scripts article on Old Persian cuneiform]\n*[http://titus.uni-frankfurt.de/personal/jg/unicode/table8.htm Old Persian cuneiform in contrast with Elamite and Late Babylonian cuneiform]\n{{Achaemenid Empire}}{{list of writing systems}}\n\n[[Category:Persian orthography]]\n[[Category:Old Persian language]]\n[[Category:Obsolete writing systems]]\n[[Category:Syllabary writing systems]]\n[[Category:Alphabets]]\n[[Category:Cuneiform]]\n[[Category:Scripts encoded in Unicode]]\n[[Category:Persian scripts]]\n", "name_user": "Biolongvistul", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Old_Persian_cuneiform"}
{"title_page": "Martin Behm", "text_new": "[[File:Martin Behm.jpg|thumb|upright|Martin Behm]]\n'''Martin Behm''' (1557&ndash;1622) was a German [[hymn]]writer.\n\nBorn in [[Lauban]] (now [[Luba\u0144]] in Poland), Behm was [[deacon]] and later chief pastor of the town's Holy Trinity Church.<ref name=nary>{{cite web|url=http://www.hymnary.org/person/Behm_Martin|work=Hymnary.org|title=Martin Behm|accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref> He wrote approximately 480 hymns, including \"Herr Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht\" (used by [[J.S. Bach]] in his cantata [[Ach_Gott,_wie_manches_Herzeleid,_BWV_58|''Ach Gott, wie manches Herzeleid'', BWV 58]]) and \"O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht\" (used by Bach for his [[O_Jesu_Christ,_meins_Lebens_Licht,_BWV_118|motet of the same name]]).<ref name=nary/> [[Carl Schalk]] wrote that Behm was among the poets at the end of the early Lutheran hymnody period who \"produced in a truly popular vein an appreciable number of excellent hymns characterized by objectivity and childlike naivete\".<ref>{{cite book|editor=Glover, Raymond F|title=The Hymnal 1982 companion|date=1994|publisher=Church Hymnal Corp.|isbn=9780898691436|pages=299|chapter=German Church Song|author=Schalk, Carl}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{NDB|2|8||Behm, Martin|Franz Lau|123261368}}\n\n{{Lutheran hymnody}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Behm, Martin}}\n[[Category:1557 births]]\n[[Category:1622 deaths]]\n[[Category:German Lutheran hymnwriters]]\n\n{{Germany-reli-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Martin Behm.jpg|thumb|upright|Martin Behm]]\n'''Martin Behm''' (1557&ndash;1622) was a German [[hymn]]writer.\n\nBorn in [[Lauban]] (now [[Luba\u0144]] in Poland), Behm was [[deacon]] and later chief pastor of the town's Holy Trinity Church.<ref name=nary>{{cite web|url=http://www.hymnary.org/person/Behm_Martin|work=Hymnary.org|title=Martin Behm|accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref> He wrote approximately 480 hymns, including \"Herr Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht\" (used by [[J.S. Bach]] in his cantata [[Ach_Gott,_wie_manches_Herzeleid,_BWV_58|''Ach Gott, wie manches Herzeleid'', BWV 58]]) and \"O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht\" (used by Bach for his [[O_Jesu_Christ,_meins_Lebens_Licht,_BWV_118|cantata of the same name]]).<ref name=nary/> [[Carl Schalk]] wrote that Behm was among the poets at the end of the early Lutheran hymnody period who \"produced in a truly popular vein an appreciable number of excellent hymns characterized by objectivity and childlike naivete\".<ref>{{cite book|editor=Glover, Raymond F|title=The Hymnal 1982 companion|date=1994|publisher=Church Hymnal Corp.|isbn=9780898691436|pages=299|chapter=German Church Song|author=Schalk, Carl}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{NDB|2|8||Behm, Martin|Franz Lau|123261368}}\n\n{{Lutheran hymnody}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Behm, Martin}}\n[[Category:1557 births]]\n[[Category:1622 deaths]]\n[[Category:German Lutheran hymnwriters]]\n\n{{Germany-reli-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Thoughtfortheday", "label": "safe", "comment": "now seen as a motet", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Martin_Behm"}
